Despite the impact Silent Spring made in the US, and subsequent rising public indignation and insistence that people be protected from corporate     and bureaucratic depredations, it took a decade for the newly established Environmental Protection Agency to ban DDT in the US, and for the passage of the     1972 Clean Air and Clean Water Acts. But unlike DDT, or CFCs, or tobacco, global warming is a non-linear threat to human health and life; it's difficult to     pin down, and thus open to the doubt and confusion sown by climate 'skeptics'.Even believers ask themselves: Which spigot should we turn off to stop the melting of the ice-caps? Who will turn off their air-conditioner first? How do     we compromise the self-evident need to reduce energy consumption with the impending increase of the world's population by a third â and that those people     will need to be clothed, housed, fed, transported and entertained to a level equivalent to that of our own cosy way of life? Sadly, as the flaccid outcomes of the Copenhagen Climate Change Conference illustrated in 2009, humans are willing to run to the very edge of     Mutually Assured Destruction.In the absence of any real sign of the changes required to address global warming, we citizen mortals, confused by the counter-arguments and bedazzled by     experts and policy honchos, can only hope to avoid MAD.In 1971, almost a decade after the publication of Silent Spring, another piece of great environmental literature was published. It's worth a read,     and especially suits those pressed for time. Written by Theodor Seuss Geiselt, better known as Dr. Seuss, the children's story The Lorax is a     fable of unrestrained human greed; not ill-intentioned greed, not wicked greed, but foolishly self-destructive greed in pursuit of a fetish â in this case     the voracious Once-ler's decimation of Truffula trees in order to manufacture Thneeds. The Once-ler notes of the last Truffula seed that where there is     life, there is hope, and life must be preserved:"Plant a new Truffula. Treat it with care. Give it clean water. And feed it fresh air."Rachel Carson would have liked that.Read more Gordon Weiss stories on the transformation of Australia from whaler to whale-watcher, the feats of 2012 Sydney Peace Prize winner Sekai Holland, and why High Speed Rail may be the answer to our transport woes.13 comments on this storyby sterbach taggartSILENT SPRINGThanks for this great article on DDT and the impact of Rachel Carson's book. Living in Darwin in the 1960's, we were regularly exposed to DDT when the council's "fogging" truck did the rounds at night, spraying out clouds of DDT to kill the mozzies which were considered to pose a threat of malaria. In this pre air-con era, Darwin houses were open via louvers for air flow, so the DDT got us whether indoors or outside. Still alive, but it's a bit like asbestos exposure, it gets some and spares others. The Darwin locals were in complete ignorance of the possible risks of DDT exposure.September 20, 2012 @ 9:26amby Jean WThe Monsanto trope inviting idiots to ingest their chemicals continues with that other time bomb, glyphosate - or more particularly the Monsanto agricultural ready-mix, "Roundup"."You can drink it" say the local farmers as they waft it around without protective gear for either themselves, their kids or their livestock.  Stock and station agents are very pleased to tell you that you could reuse the Roundup drums for drinking water, "it's a harmless salt"As the evidence mounts that the surfactant is the crueller of the long-term poisons in their mix - too many waterways de-populated of everything from beetles to frogs - Monsanto are happy to produce a pre-mixed glyphosate with fewer waterway harms, but still flog the basic "Roundup" without check.September 20, 2012 @ 10:23amby PaulOne of the many great myths in this area is that DDT has been banned on a worldwide basis.  It has never been banned for vector control.  It has been banned for agricultural use - which gives it a longer life as a vector control because it slows down the rate of vector adaptation.September 20, 2012 @ 11:46amby John EgertonAs a vet in Port Moresby in the fifties and sixties we too were fogged twice weekly with DDT. My family and I survived and never had malaria which is endemic in PNG. There was no evidence that the DDT was lethal for animals other than insects. The geckos which shared our houses were unaffected nor was there any sign of toxicity in the town's dogs and cats. The major problem with DDT was its accumulation in the food chain leading to reproductive failure in birds and other animals. The next chlorinated hydrocarbon, dieldrin, was much more toxic but was used for many years to control external parasites on livestock in Australia and elsewhere. It too was later banned for this purpose.September 20, 2012 @ 4:03pmby RothaAh! the wisdom of hindsight.DDT was considered poisonous at last, but its modern equivalent, Glyphosateis still described as 'So safe you can drink it' by those who have been conveniently miss-informed in so called seminars by hired scientists. Weeds have replaced insects as the supposed enemies of mankind. Weeds, it seems are depriving farmers of thousands of dollars.... Inexpensive tests are available to find Glyphosate in Great Barrier Reef waters but no-one looks for it. Farmers are blamed for turbid waters in rivers and sea but applications of Glyphosate by State and Federal Governments and Councils all through the year are never considered dangerous to Rivers, Harbours and The Barrier Reef. Wild life suffer the same stomach, liver and kidney problems as livestock fed on GMOs. Does one need to be a scientist to suspect Glyphosate?September 22, 2012 @ 12:05amby Roger KellyHanging on a wall in my bathroom is a framed original page from "The Australian Women's Weekly", page 30 dated January 30th 1952.It is a full page ad for Taylor's (Later Mortein Taylor) 'Number 13' household insecticide, containing "A double action killer! - Tested Trusted D.D.T. together with the new, safe, amazing miracle Benzene Hexachloride"There are two corny graphics at the top of the page: one showing husband in striped PJs, lovingly spraying above his sleeping wife, and the other showing wife happily spraing the food cupboards in the kitchen.The text variously describes Number 13 as "...the world's safest insecticide / completely safe /  incredibly effective." Buyers are advised to "Just spray it on walls, ceilings. skirting boards, hanging clothes, into cupboards, on rubbish tins..."This was sold in "8oz bottles, and, the family economy size - a full pint to last all summer"I was born in 1954 and I know the this was used in our home.  I have health issues and have forever wondered what current health problems were caused and/or exacerbated by DDT in our lives.  I feel terribly defeated in the certainty I'll never know.  Neither will countless other Australians.September 23, 2012 @ 7:18amby Oanist MisanthorpeWell done Ms Carson...BUT... 50 years ? Look back to Henry David Thoreau "What use a house if we don't have a Planet to put it on"Prescience indeedSeptember 30, 2012 @ 9:25pmby Keith ThomasA masterly explication of the mixing of science and politics in the context of our particular arrangement of capitalism. You make it clear how business initiates a proxy war using rigged "science", emotion, and deceit to mask their real war which is about increasing profits. One sad aspect of this is that business can motivate frightened little people to do their bidding in the trenches - for example drafting and displaying "Ditch the witch" signs at political rallies - without realizing the extent to which they are being manipulated. Thanks again. Nice piece of work. (I wouldn't mind seeing a "most popular stores" list on this website, as I expect this one would feature on it for a long time.)October 13, 2012 @ 2:28amby Mike gA flawed book designed mainly to promote the career of Rachel Carson.June 10, 2013 @ 7:05amby JmichaelShe did not need career enhancement!November 4, 2013 @ 3:53pmShow previous 10 comments
